Document: 2D and 3D Physics Interpolation  
Path: godot/tutorials/physics/interpolation/2d_and_3d_physics_interpolation.rst  
Summary: Recommendations for using CPUParticles2D in 2D physics interpolation and limitations of Particles2D.  

Currently only CPUParticles2D are supported for physics interpolation in 2D. It is recommended to use a physics tick rate of at least 20-30 ticks per second to keep particles looking fluid. Particles2D (GPU particles) are not yet interpolated, so for now it is recommended to convert to CPUParticles2D (but keep a backup of your Particles2D in case we get these working).
---CHUNK---
Document: 2d_and_3d_physics_interpolation  
Path: godot/tutorials/physics/interpolation/2d_and_3d_physics_interpolation.rst  
Summary: Key differences between 2D and 3D physics interpolation implementations in Godot.  

- ``get_global_transform_interpolated()`` is currently only available for 3D.  
- ``MultiMeshes`` are supported in both 2D and 3D.  
- Physics interpolation in 2D is implemented on the server side, which means it's effective on physics bodies created using low-level servers. In contrast, physics interpolation in 3D is implemented on the scene side. This means it does not affect physics bodies created using servers. These must be interpolated manually instead. See the pull request description for the rationale on this design decision.